BA2-4F5A-826B-43504F8FB1EC</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Andriy</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Myachykov</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE02498X%2F1"><gtr:id>CB3BB333-645F-4C97-9CAC-BB0A4187E9C8</gtr:id><gtr:title>Integrating perceptual, semantic, and syntactic information during sentence production.</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E02498X/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Existing research suggests that world-situated sentence production relies on complex interactions between non-linguistic (perceptual) and linguistic (grammatical) information. These interactions are regulated by the language-perception interface established between the domain-general and the domain-specific cognitive processes. The current project will use the current experimental evidence and the resulting theoretical framework for better formalization of the processes involved in the world-situated real-time sentence production across languages with different grammatical systems. The new research will capitalize on the previous investigations and use the eye-tracking methodology to further analyze how people?s grammatical choices vary dependent on the properties of the perceived world and the organization of the language grammar. Prepared and submitted publications as well as conference presentations will summarize the experimental and theoretical findings. Longer-term research developments will include the analysis of how language-perception interface develops in young children, operates in a bilingual, and in a language-impaired mind (eg, Broca's aphasia).&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-10-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6